<br>
OK, pretty funny, but give me a break. I seriously doubt you all look at life this negatively overall <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
LDS belief is that leaving the garden of Eden was opening the door to mortality (you know, mortality, it's a good thing overall), not something that &quot;poisened&quot; us all. Adam and Eve opened the door into mortality for everyone and Christ opened the door back out for everyone (remember, LDS believe we will all be resurrected and go to some level of heaven). No one was &quot;punished&quot; for something they didn't do.<br>
<br>
And you know, I was thinking today about what a horrible parent my neighbor is. She actually purchased a bike for her child. They mutually agreed that he could ride it and she also purchased and suggested that he wear his helmet and then taught him the rules of safety.<br>
<br>
Well, of course as soon as he was out of her sight he took the helmet off and recklessly careened across their lawn where her two  smaller children were playing an knocked  them down, then fell down himself and hit his head. One of the little kids was hurt pretty badly. It was terrible.<br>
<br>
What kind of parent lets their kid get a bike anyway? Obviousy she is sadistic and egotistical for providing a situation where that could happen. She should have bought a tandem bike and been with him every second of every day to make sure she could force him to follow the safety rules. Sure, he wouldn't gain the same experience or knowledge had he been allowed to try it on his own at some point, and sure, not every child would have done what he did and most would have a great experience and not hurt anyone else, but it is still completely sick and wrong for parents to provide these opportunities to children.<br>
<br>
Don't you agree?<br>
<br>
