<br>
Multiply it by several hundreds of millions of the horrendous suffering, and have Mom standing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>right there</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and being perfectly capable of stopping it, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>still</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> letting it happen &quot;for the growth and experience&quot;, then yeah, I agree.<br>
<br>
Heidi, are you saying that God isn't around (He's off playing golf or something) and that we are basically on our own, or are you saying He isn't capable of intervening, or something else?<br>
<br>
Here's a counter-analogy. Chris was walking along the street one day and he heard a woman screaming, clearly in distress. He ran to see what was going on, and found a teenage punk beating her and raping her. Chris is a big guy, and he's been involved in a few street fights and has had some training. But he decides to walk away. After all,<br>
<br>
(A) God has given us &quot;free will&quot; to live with our decisions, so both the perp and the woman will have to live with the consequences of the decisions that brought them to that point;<br>
<br>
(B) the perp will learn from his experience, and in his old age he will come to regret the wrongfulness of his decisions and actions;<br>
<br>
(C) the lady will grow stronger from her suffering;<br>
<br>
(D) God's going to punish the transgressions appropriately anyway after we die;<br>
<br>
(E) since God has given us &quot;Free Will&quot;, they who are we to intervene in someone else's choices and actions, even if someone else is inordinately hurt?<br>
<br>
Clearly, Chris was acting (by not intervening) much as God does, don't you think?<br>
<br>
