<br>
In the Garden, when Adam and Eve made a choice to follow their own will, instead of God’s will, they stepped out on their own. Evil existed at that time, but within the Garden, as long as they obeyed God, Adam and Eve were immune from the results of evil. They were still subject to temptation, but since they (at that time) had no sin, they were not subject to the consequences of it. There was no death, no disease, no suffering. <br>
<br>
When they sinned—when they exercised their choice, they subjected themselves to the natural consequences of sin. God told them that they would now be subject to death and that things would be “hard” for them. By the sweat of their brow, they would now have to deal with the consequences of evil.<br>
<br>
So many questions that people have with the concept of God revolves around why a loving God would allow suffering and evil in the first place. Surely a sovereign God would be powerful enough to destroy Evil. Indeed we are told in the Bible that Satan, death and even evil itself will be destroyed, but not until its time. <br>
<br>
So, why wait? Why not just do away with evil now, end the suffering and be done with the whole business of sin? The answer, I believe is found in the books of Job and Isaiah. The theme running through the book of Job delineates the conflict between good and evil. The theme running through the book of Isaiah is the remedy to the conflict, the mission of the Messiah. In these two books (as well as other places) we see in the conflict, an accuser, accusing God of being arbitrary and that God incites obedience by either promises of favor or by fear, rather than by love. In the Book of Job Satan asserts that Job only obeys God because God has blessed him and that if God were to remove his blessings and allow him, the accuser, to inflict harm, that Job would curse God. <br>
<br>
I do believe the story of Job is literal (many believe it to only be allegorical), however I also believe it is told to give us a kind of behind-the-scenes peek at who causes our suffering and difficulties in life, and why a loving God allows it.<br>
<br>
Also, I believe God has allowed humanity to experiment with sin to provide a means to end it, forever. When Christ returns to gather his elect, God will have representatives in humanity who have experience with rebellion and sin, who clung to the Blood of Christ for salvation. The saved will be witnesses to the heavenly beings, the angels and all heavenly creation to demonstrate in living fashion God’s great love for us. They have already seen the great love of God on the cross. Then they will have eyewitness accounts from those who have lived in sin, and know destitution first hand.<br>
<br>
Drug addicts can testify how God lifted them from despair and gave them hope. Adulterers can testify how God forgave and saved their marriages. Murderers can testify how God replace hatred with love in their hearts. Liars can testify how God restored to them, truth. Sinners can testify how God reconciled them to life, turning them away from sin. <br>
<br>
Sin goes on for now, perhaps so that the universe, looking on, may see how rebellion turns to sin; how sin turns to despair; how despair turns into suffering and death. In the end, evil will be destroyed, and for those who are saved, and the heavenly beings, rebellion and sin will not be an option--by choice! <br>
<br>
Regards<br>
<br>
Jeff <br>
<br>
<br>
