<br>
Job as a story only works if you don't look at anything aside from Job.  Sure, he was beat on by the adversary on a bet with god.  Sure god tossed out every rule each time the adversary teased him (how easy is THIS guy to manipulate?) Somehow, this freewilled independant spirit is okay to abuse by god because people seem okay with thinking of themselves as god's property, especially in light of their eternal salvation.  Any arbitrary level of abuse is okay so long as they get to valhalla.  Sure.<br>
<br>
What about Job's wives and children?  All of them were killed and stolen and destroied to work this bet.  Any of them who were not saved were cheated by god for claiming them (or allowing them to be claimed) before their time and opportunity to redeem themselves.  If god just 'let them in' for being in his little bet, then what does that mean in terms of the worth of salvation?  Why do some have to work so damn hard (like Job did) and others get a free pass for being extras in the play?  If you say god 'just knew' who would be saved and they weren't on the list then you toss out the idea of free will entirely.<br>
<br>
Drug addicts, murderers, adulterers, deceivers, and 'sinners' all bask in the love of god?  What a wonderful crowd to hang out with.  Perhaps they need the deception of god to give them strength because they lack the faith in themselves to do it on their own.  Like Dumbo learning to fly, only holding the magic crucifix instead of the magic feather.  God the Father, Son and Holy Crutch.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A man at the bar turns to this woman next to him and asks her, &quot;Will you sleep with me for a million dollars?&quot;  She looks at him and says, &quot;A million dollars?  Sure!&quot;  He takes a sip from his drink and says, &quot;OK how about 20 dollars?&quot;  She looks at him appaled and says, &quot;What do I look like to you, a whore?&quot; He replies, &quot;Lady we already established you are a whore, the rest is just haggling over the price.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> God abused Job, worse he slaughtered the innocents of his family.  Abuse is abuse and if you can only differentiate it in terms of degree it is a poor argument all around.  You cannot beat the crap out of your spouse or child then buy them icecream or jewelry to make it better.  God cannot beat the crap out of his children and thern pay them off with Elisium to make that any better either. <p><br>
